         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="zoor0192.translation"
              corresp="#zoor0192.transcription">
            <p>One (is) the God, who helps. Monument of Paulus, (son) of Sammasas, who died
                    having a good name and good faith (at the age) of 65 years, in the year 347, on
                    (the) 25th (day) of (the) month Xanthikos, on (the) 4th day of (the) Lord
                    (Wednesday). Be of good cheer, no one (is) immortal.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription provides the date as the 4th day of the Lord, the 25th of the month Xanthikos, in the year 347 according to the Era of the Province of Arabia, that is, April 15, 452 CE. The tombstone is one of about 700 discovered in Byzantine Zoora. The majority of the Greek tombstones from this location have been identified as Christian. The nearly rectangular tombstone is curved at the top and lower right corner. Written in predominantly square script with a few round exceptions, the text is engraved upon a smoothed surface, which is chipped in a few places and weathered in the upper right section. Incised, red-painted guide-lines appear underneath the first two lines. Lines two, four, six, and eight are painted over in red. Three decorative figures appear below the inscription, all of which are engraved and painted red: a central, outlined cross with a chi-sign in the middle, flanked by two birds filled with a linear pattern. The text and these figures are surrounded by a vaulted, incised, and red-painted frame on all sides except for the bottom. The sides of this frame are decorated with a red-painted motif, which resembles leaves. A horizontal bar appears above the abbreviation of βοηθός in line one, the age and year numerals in line six, the month day numeral in line seven, and the weekday numeral in line eight. The text contains both spelling and grammatical errors. The phrase εἷς Θεὸς βοηθός is a variant of εἷς Θεὸς ὁ βοηθῶν.</p>
         </div>
